`template/scripts/` is the CI/lint gate suite for projects scaffolded from this template, plus the two scripts that keep such a project's tooling in sync with the upstream CTX repo. Depending on this directory means: running these scripts gives you offline-safe static checks (no cargo/network needed except where noted) that ctx-verify treats as pass/fail signals, and running `update-template.sh` gives you a one-command refresh of all of the above from upstream.

The check scripts (`cycle_check.sh`, `machete_check.sh`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`) share a file-enumeration convention: all but `cycle_check.sh` and `machete_check.sh` (which shell out to external tools) use `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard` rather than a filesystem walk, specifically to avoid racing concurrent writes into `target/`. Changing any of them to `find`/`rglob` reintroduces that hazard — this is a load-bearing convention shared across files, not a per-file detail. Two of the five (`cycle_check.sh`, `machete_check.sh`) are placeholders or wrappers around external binaries (`cargo-modules`, `cargo-machete`) that must be installed separately and hard-fail if missing; the other three are self-contained.

`install-tools.sh` and `update-template.sh` are coupled: the latter calls the former for binaries/prompts, then unconditionally overwrites this directory's own check scripts (among other files) from the upstream CTX repo checkout — meaning any local edit to a script in this directory is destroyed the next time `update-template.sh` runs. `update-template.sh` also self-overwrites last, after everything else, since Bash can't safely rewrite a running multi-step script mid-execution.

Invariant across the five check scripts: each exits 0 only on a clean pass and 1 on any failure or missing-tool condition, with `FAIL: <path>:<line>:...`-style output that downstream ctx-verify parses — changing that output shape breaks the parser silently, as `machete_check.sh`'s notes flag for its own case.